s are loyal to Android brands. (Apple is trying to reach more of these cons=
umers through trade-in programs and older iPhone models at lower prices, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s an uphill battle).

All these factors help explain why Apple=E2=80=99s China sales have seesawe=
d with iPhone product cycles rather than showing steady growth. When a *mus=
t-have model* arrives (e.g. the larger-screen iPhone 6, or the first 5G iPh=
one 12), Apple sees a surge in China as its base upgrades and a chunk of An=
droid users switch to get the new hot device. But in between, without new a=
ddressable market segments, sales can fall off. Tim Cook has often pointed =
to macroeconomic or temporary issues, but the bigger picture is a near-satu=
ration of Apple=E2=80=99s feasible market in China.

This quarter=E2=80=99s *11% drop* in Greater China revenue fits that narrat=
ive =E2=80=93 it coincided with soft iPhone 15 demand in China and intensif=
ying local competition. In fact, Apple is now dealing with a new twist: the=
