Huawei=E2=80=99s absence in the high-end market due to U.S. sanctions that =
cut Huawei off from 5G chips. During 2020-2022, Huawei=E2=80=99s smartphone=
 sales plunged, and many Chinese consumers who might have bought a Huawei f=
lagship instead chose an iPhone. This boost was evident in Apple=E2=80=99s =
rising China revenue through 2021 and especially 2022. By *2023, Apple even=
 became the #1 smartphone vendor in China* by units, capturing about *17.3%=
 market share* =E2=80=93 a record for Apple ( idc.com ( https://www.idc.com=
/getdoc.jsp?containerId=3DprAP51817224#:~:text=3DApple%20Captures%20the%20T=
op%20Spot,in%202023 ) ) =E2=80=93 largely because Huawei (formerly the mark=
et leader) was sidelined. *That advantage has proven temporary.*

Late last year, Huawei stunned the industry with the launch of the *Mate 60=
 Pro* , a flagship phone sporting a domestically made 7nm 5G chip, effectiv=
ely overcoming (to an extent) the U.S. chip ban. Chinese consumers, fed by =
a mix of patriotism and pent-up demand for a new Huawei device, flocked to =
the Mate 60. The effect on Apple was immediate: by Q4 2024, Huawei had reas=
serted itself and *Apple=E2=80=99s iPhone shipments in China fell roughly 2=
0=E2=80=9325%* year-on-year ( cnbc.com ( https://www.cnbc.com/2025/01/16/ap=
ple-fourt-iphone-shipments-in-china-drop-as-huawei-closes-in.html#:~:text=
=3DCNBC%20www,of%20mounting%20pressure%20from%20Huawei ) ). Market research=
ers reported Huawei overtaking Apple in unit sales in the quarter, and for =
full-year 2024 Apple fell back to *third place* in China=E2=80=99s smartpho=
ne market (with ~15% share, behind Vivo and Huawei) ( reuters.com ( https:/=
/www.reuters.com/technology/apple-smartphone-shipments-china-fell-25-q4-can=
alys-says-2025-01-16/#:~:text=3D2024%20www,iPhone%20maker%20after%20its ) )=
. In other words, the *=E2=80=9CHuawei ban bump=E2=80=9D* for Apple has rev=
ersed. Apple=E2=80=99s $72B China revenue in FY2023 =E2=80=93 which was alr=
eady below the 2015 level in real terms =E2=80=93 slid to ~$67B in FY2024 (=
 s2.q4cdn.com ( https://s2.q4cdn.com/470004039/files/doc_earnings/2024/q4/f=
iling/10-Q4-2024-As-Filed.pdf#:~:text=3D2024%20Change%202023%20Change%20202=
2,to%202023%20due%20primarily%20to ) ), and the latest quarter indicates co=
ntinued decline. The *competitive landscape* has fundamentally changed agai=
n: Huawei is aggressively targeting the premium segment (even launching mor=
e new models in early 2025), and other Chinese OEMs are pushing premium mod=
els too. Apple now faces a revitalized local competitor that it did not for=
 the past 3-4 years. The *temporary reprieve* that U.S. sanctions granted A=
pple in China=E2=80=99s high-end market is clearly over =E2=80=93 it was a =
*one-time boost* rather than a permanent conquest.

What does this imply for Apple=E2=80=99s prospects in China? In the near te=
rm, it suggests caution. Apple may need to temper expectations for growth i=
n China or invest in strategies beyond just premium iPhones to re-ignite mo=
mentum. The company has been trying to localize more (e.g. more regional fe=
atures, financing options, and even moving some production to India to dive=
rsify geopolitical risk). Tim Cook also alluded to hoping for *economic sti=
mulus in China* to spur consumer spending ( news.alphastreet.com ( https://=
news.alphastreet.com/aapl-q1-2025-call-highlights-china-challenges-india-st=
rategy-and-market-expansion/#:~:text=3DApple%20Intelligence%20was%20availab=
le,Tim%20Cook%20%E2%80%93%20CEO ) ) =E2=80=93 essentially, Apple could use =
a macroeconomic tailwind, as China=E2=80=99s economy and consumer sentiment=
 have been relatively weak. But macro factors aside, the structural issues =
remain: *Apple is largely confined to the mature high-end niche* of the Chi=
nese market. Unless Apple devises a way to appeal further downmarket (which=
 seems unlikely given its brand positioning), China may continue to be a st=
ory of *replacement sales and competitive tug-of-war* rather than a growth =
engine. Indeed, Apple=E2=80=99s long-term bet might be that as China=E2=80=
=99s middle class affluence grows, the pool of people who can afford iPhone=
s will slowly expand =E2=80=93 but that=E2=80=99s a gradual secular trend, =
not the kind of explosive growth of a decade ago.

In sum, Apple=E2=80=99s decline in China does look like part of a *long-run=
ning pattern* rather than an aberration. The company hit an early peak in t=
he mid-2010s, struggled through late-2010s, got a boost when a key rival wa=
s hobbled, and now is dealing with a reversion to the mean. China remains a=
 crucial market (roughly 15=E2=80=9320% of Apple=E2=80=99s revenue) and imm=
ensely profitable, but it is *Apple=E2=80=99s most challenging market* as w=
ell =E2=80=93 one that may no longer provide much growth without either *ma=
rket expansion (new customers)* or *major product innovation* that pulls pe=
ople off of WeChat and Android. The latest quarter=E2=80=99s drop and the H=
uawei dynamic underscore that reality.

AI and =E2=80=9CApple Intelligence=E2=80=9D: New Features, Limited Impact?

The third key theme from Apple=E2=80=99s earnings call was *AI =E2=80=93 sp=
ecifically Apple=E2=80=99s approach to integrating AI, which it brands =E2=
=80=9CApple Intelligence.=E2=80=9D* Unlike its Big Tech peers, Apple hasn=
=E2=80=99t launched a flashy, chatty generative AI chatbot or a public AI r=
esearch demo. Instead, Apple=E2=80=99s strategy is to weave AI-driven featu=
res *quietly into its products* , leveraging on-device processing (thanks t=
o Apple Silicon) to enhance user experiences. At the iPhone 15 launch and i=
n iOS updates, Apple rolled out a suite of new AI-powered capabilities =E2=
=80=93 and on the earnings call, Tim Cook and team actually credited these =
features with helping drive iPhone sales in the markets where they=E2=80=99=
re available.

Apple Intelligence features reportedly include things like:

* *Writing Tools* =E2=80=93 AI-assisted text capabilities (e.g. enhanced au=
tocorrect and predictive text that can even finish your sentences more cont=
extually).
* *Image Playground* =E2=80=93 presumably a feature to create or manipulate=
 images via AI (possibly allowing users to generate images or apply AI effe=
cts).
* *Genmoji* =E2=80=93 a generative emoji or avatar feature, perhaps creatin=
g custom emoji stickers based on text prompts or user likeness.
* *Clean Up* =E2=80=93 an AI-driven photo editing function to remove unwant=
ed objects or imperfections from images (similar to Google=E2=80=99s Magic =
Eraser).

These features were cited as being *widely used with promising early adopti=
on* in the launch markets ( news.alphastreet.com ( https://news.alphastreet=
.com/aapl-q1-2025-call-highlights-china-challenges-india-strategy-and-marke=
t-expansion/#:~:text=3D,Tim%20Cook%20%E2%80%93%20CEO ) ). Essentially, Appl=
e is saying that the new iPhones (the =E2=80=9CiPhone 16 models=E2=80=9D as=
 the call transcript put it =E2=80=93 likely referring to the iPhone 15 fam=
ily) are more attractive because of these AI-powered capabilities branded u=
nder Apple Intelligence. And indeed, Apple noted that *iPhone 15/16 models =
performed better in regions where Apple Intelligence is available* ( news.a=
lphastreet.com ( https://news.alphastreet.com/aapl-q1-2025-call-highlights-=
china-challenges-india-strategy-and-market-expansion/#:~:text=3D,Tim%20Cook=
%20%E2%80%93%20CEO ) ). This specifically came up when discussing why China=
=E2=80=99s iPhone sales lagged: Apple Intelligence had *not launched in Chi=
na* , and this =E2=80=9Caffected iPhone replacement cycles=E2=80=9D there a=
ccording to Tim Cook ( news.alphastreet.com ( https://news.alphastreet.com/=
aapl-q1-2025-call-highlights-china-challenges-india-strategy-and-market-exp=
ansion/#:~:text=3DApple%20Intelligence%20was%20available,Tim%20Cook%20%E2%8=
0%93%20CEO ) ). In other words, Apple believes (or at least wants analysts =
to believe) that lack of those AI features made Chinese consumers less comp=
elled to upgrade to the new iPhone, whereas in markets like the U.S. or Eur=
ope, the AI features provided an extra incentive to buy or upgrade.

It=E2=80=99s intriguing that Apple is explicitly tying *AI to sales perform=
ance* , because historically Apple tends to downplay tech jargon like =E2=
=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D in marketing. The company clearly sees =E2=80=9CApple Int=
elligence=E2=80=9D as a differentiator it can talk up. And to some extent, =
this narrative makes sense: rival smartphone makers (Google with its Pixels=
, Samsung, etc.) have been touting AI features (camera tricks, voice assist=
ants, etc.) for a while. Apple injecting *on-device generative AI* capabili=
ties could indeed make its products more appealing, or at least help it kee=
p pace in the features race. There=E2=80=99s also a practical element: cert=
ain AI features (like advanced language models for Siri or translation) nee=
d hefty processing or aren=E2=80=99t fully localized, so Apple staged a rol=
lout =E2=80=93 they might be in English and a few languages now, with more =
coming later (Tim Cook mentioned Apple Intelligence will be available =E2=
=80=9Cin even more languages this April=E2=80=9D ( apple.com ( https://www.=
apple.com/newsroom/2025/01/apple-reports-first-quarter-results/#:~:text=3D%=
E2%80%9CToday%20Apple%20is%20reporting%20our,%E2%80%9D ) )). That implies C=
hina (and Chinese language support) might be on the roadmap but wasn=E2=80=
=99t ready by 2024.

So, is Apple=E2=80=99s AI push moving the needle? The answer is *yes =E2=80=
=93 but only slightly, and only where available.* Apple indicated that *iPh=
one upgrade rates hit an all-time high* this quarter ( news.alphastreet.com=
 ( https://news.alphastreet.com/aapl-q1-2025-call-highlights-china-challeng=
es-india-strategy-and-market-expansion/#:~:text=3D,Tim%20Cook%20%E2%80%93%2=
0CEO ) ), and that the latest iPhone outsold the previous generation, parti=
ally thanks to Apple Intelligence features enticing users in markets like N=
orth America and India. This claim suggests AI was a selling point: early a=
dopters may have been drawn to things like being able to create custom emoj=
is or magically clean up photos on the new iPhone. It=E2=80=99s a testament=
 to Apple=E2=80=99s brand power that even without shouting =E2=80=9CAI=E2=
=80=9D from the rooftops, they can integrate it in a way consumers just use=
 it as part of the device=E2=80=99s value. In those markets, Apple can say =
AI helped differentiate the iPhone 15 from both older iPhones and competing=
 devices.

However, *the overall impact on Apple=E2=80=99s business so far is limited*=
 by two factors: geography and scope. First, these Apple Intelligence featu=
res are absent in China (and perhaps other regions/languages) for now. Chin=
a is one of Apple=E2=80=99s largest iPhone markets; if AI features are infl=
uencing buyers elsewhere but zero in China, the global boost is muted. In f=
act, one could cynically interpret Apple=E2=80=99s comments as partly an ex=
cuse : =E2=80=9COur China sales are down, but only because those poor custo=
mers don=E2=80=99t yet have our cool AI features =E2=80=93 once we roll tho=
se out, maybe they=E2=80=99ll upgrade.=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=99s truth in Ch=
inese consumers missing out on new features, but it=E2=80=99s unlikely that=
 alone caused the 11% revenue drop (economic factors and Huawei=E2=80=99s c=
ompetition are larger drivers). Still, Apple is effectively acknowledging t=
hat *Apple Intelligence isn=E2=80=99t a factor in China* , and until it is,=
 AI won=E2=80=99t help fix Apple=E2=80=99s biggest weak spot. So long as AI=
 is not available globally, its contribution to overall growth is inherentl=
y capped.

Second, it=E2=80=99s unclear how compelling these AI features truly are in =
driving incremental sales. Are users buying an iPhone 15 specifically becau=
se it can do Genmoji or advanced autocorrect? Or is it just a nice bonus fo=
r those who were going to upgrade anyway? Apple says early usage is strong =
( news.alphastreet.com ( https://news.alphastreet.com/aapl-q1-2025-call-hig=
hlights-china-challenges-india-strategy-and-market-expansion/#:~:text=3D,Ti=
m%20Cook%20%E2%80%93%20CEO ) ), which is encouraging =E2=80=93 it means peo=
ple are finding these features useful or fun. Over time, if Apple Intellige=
nce develops into something more transformative (say, a much smarter Siri t=
hat can act as a real personal assistant), that could indeed become a major=
 selling point. But at this stage, the AI features seem mostly *quality-of-=
life improvements* rather than must-have killer apps. In the absence of a s=
ingle headline AI feature (like a ChatGPT-like assistant integrated deeply =
into iOS), the impact might be more defensive =E2=80=93 i.e. keeping iPhone=
 at feature parity (or slightly ahead) of Android rivals =E2=80=93 rather t=
han opening a new floodgate of device demand.

It=E2=80=99s also worth noting Apple=E2=80=99s philosophical difference: Ap=
ple emphasizes *privacy and on-device processing*. Its AI features are run =
on the Neural Engine in Apple=E2=80=99s chips, not big cloud servers. This =
limits some capabilities (Apple=E2=80=99s models might be smaller than what=
 a cloud AI could do), but it aligns with Apple=E2=80=99s brand on privacy.=
 It also means Apple is somewhat late to certain AI arenas =E2=80=93 for ex=
ample, there=E2=80=99s no Apple equivalent yet of the AI chatbots or genera=
tive image creators that companies like Microsoft, Google, and OpenAI are p=
ushing. Apple might integrate a large language model into Siri in the futur=
e, but it will likely do so cautiously. All told, Apple=E2=80=99s approach =
to AI is evolutionary, not revolutionary: making the iPhone a bit smarter i=
n ways that complement the hardware. As Tim Cook put it, =E2=80=9Cthrough t=
he power of Apple silicon, we=E2=80=99re unlocking new possibilities for ou=
r users with Apple Intelligence, which makes apps and experiences even bett=
er and more personal.=E2=80=9D ( apple.com ( https://www.apple.com/newsroom=
/2025/01/apple-reports-first-quarter-results/#:~:text=3D%E2%80%9CToday%20Ap=
ple%20is%20reporting%20our,%E2%80%9D ) ) It=E2=80=99s a classic Apple move =
=E2=80=93 tie the software capability to the hardware advantage (fast chips=
) to deliver something competitors might struggle to match as seamlessly.

From a *market impact* perspective, the *AI factor has been positive but ma=
rginal*. It may have helped iPhone 15 series perform slightly better than i=
t otherwise would have in the West =E2=80=93 Apple noted the new lineup =E2=
=80=9Coutperformed iPhone 15=E2=80=9D (meaning better than last year=E2=80=
=99s) in terms of upgrades ( news.alphastreet.com ( https://news.alphastree=
t.com/aapl-q1-2025-call-highlights-china-challenges-india-strategy-and-mark=
et-expansion/#:~:text=3D,Tim%20Cook%20%E2%80%93%20CEO ) ), which is saying =
something given last year=E2=80=99s iPhone 14 cycle was soft. But it did no=
t prevent overall iPhone revenue from declining year-on-year (iPhone revenu=
e was down ~8% YoY globally) and it didn=E2=80=99t prevent Apple=E2=80=99s =
biggest iPhone market (China) from slumping. So any AI-driven sales boost w=
as *not enough to fully counter other headwinds*. And because Apple isn=E2=
=80=99t monetizing AI as a separate service (it=E2=80=99s a value-add to de=
vices), the impact is seen in hardware units/revenue and Services usage, no=
t a direct new revenue stream.

One could argue that *Apple=E2=80=99s AI rollout is mostly about keeping it=
s ecosystem sticky*. If features like Writing Tools or Image Playground del=
ight users, they strengthen the user experience and satisfaction, which in =
turn supports upgrade cycles and Services engagement. It=E2=80=99s a subtle=
, long-term play rather than a short-term sales gimmick. And importantly, A=
pple=E2=80=99s focus on on-device AI means that when these features do laun=
ch in China (assuming they can overcome language and possibly regulatory hu=
rdles), Chinese users will get them without Apple needing any government ap=
provals (since it=E2=80=99s not a cloud service that might get blocked =E2=
=80=93 everything happens on the device). So the limitation is technical fo=
r now, not necessarily permanent. By next year, Apple Intelligence might be=
 global, and at that point Apple could claim a more uniform benefit from AI=
 in driving customer satisfaction and upgrades worldwide.

*Bottom line on AI:* Apple is integrating AI in a characteristically Apple =
way =E2=80=93 enhancing products rather than hyping a standalone AI. They a=
re already leveraging it as a talking point to explain regional differences=
 in performance (with an eye toward future upside once rolled out universal=
ly). In markets like the US, AI features likely contributed to making the i=
Phone 15 a more compelling upgrade, but it=E2=80=99s hard to disentangle ho=
w much of the sales is due to =E2=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D versus, say, the camera =
improvements or simply the natural replacement cycle. Meanwhile, in China, =
the lack of these features might have marginally hurt the iPhone=E2=80=99s =
appeal, but it=E2=80=99s one factor among many (and probably smaller than t=
he Huawei effect or economic softness). So, at this stage *Apple=E2=80=99s =
AI push is a modest tailwind, not a game-changer*. It=E2=80=99s more about =
keeping the ecosystem competitive and laying groundwork for the future than=
 about immediate financial impact. If and when Apple delivers a breakthroug=
h AI-driven user experience (for example, a truly smart Siri or AR experien=
ces powered by AI on Apple Vision Pro), then AI could become a more materia=
l driver of device sales and usage. For now, Apple Intelligence is *one pie=
ce of the puzzle* =E2=80=93 helpful in certain markets, absent in others =
=E2=80=93 but not the centerpiece of Apple=E2=80=99s growth story yet.

*Conclusion*

Apple=E2=80=99s Q1 FY2025 earnings encapsulate the company=E2=80=99s evolvi=
ng strategy and the cross-currents it must navigate. *Services* have solidi=
fied Apple=E2=80=99s transformation into a company as much about software a=
nd subscriptions as about hardware =E2=80=93 this high-margin, steady growt=
h segment is cushioning Apple=E2=80=99s results and will likely be the key =
to future earnings expansion. *China* remains Apple=E2=80=99s largest geogr=
aphic challenge: it=E2=80=99s a market that fueled Apple=E2=80=99s rise a d=
ecade ago but now appears near saturation for the premium segment, with rev=
ived local competition (Huawei) and ecosystem nuances that dilute Apple=E2=
=80=99s traditional advantages. And *AI (=E2=80=9CApple Intelligence=E2=80=
=9D)* represents both an emerging opportunity and a talking point =E2=80=93=
 it=E2=80=99s Apple=E2=80=99s answer to the industry=E2=80=99s AI wave, imp=
lemented in a way that aligns with Apple=E2=80=99s product philosophy. It m=
ay not radically boost sales overnight, but it=E2=80=99s an investment in k=
eeping Apple=E2=80=99s user experience best-in-class, which in the long run=
 supports the entire ecosystem of device sales and services.

For investors and observers, the takeaway is that Apple=E2=80=99s core stor=
y is one of *resilience and adaptation*. The company is wringing more value=
 out of its existing customer base through services and incremental innovat=
ions, even as it faces the reality of a maturing smartphone market. The lat=
est earnings show Apple can still grow (record revenue, record EPS ( apple.=
com ( https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2025/01/apple-reports-first-quarter-re=
sults/#:~:text=3DCUPERTINO%2C%20CALIFORNIA%20Apple%20today%20announced,10%2=
0percent%20year%20over%20year ) )) in a tough environment =E2=80=93 thanks =
to the shift toward services and loyalty of its users =E2=80=93 but also th=
at *growth won=E2=80=99t be uniform across markets or product lines*. The S=
ervices boom and the China malaise are two sides of that coin. Looking ahea=
d, Apple=E2=80=99s ability to sustain momentum will hinge on continuing to =
execute in services (where it=E2=80=99s strong now), finding ways to re-ene=
rgize iPhone demand in places like China (a harder task, possibly requiring=
 new price points or breakthrough features), and capitalizing on new techno=
logy transitions (be it AI or AR/VR with Vision Pro) to spark the next grow=
th cycle.

In classic Stratechery fashion, one might frame Apple=E2=80=99s position as=
 straddling the line between *harvesting its past successes and planting se=
eds for the future*. The Services surge is the harvest from over a billion =
devices in use =E2=80=93 an enviable position that no competitor can easily=
 replicate. The China predicament and the AI rollout are part of the seed-p=
lanting: how Apple adapts to a changing world (whether that=E2=80=99s geopo=
litical shifts or the AI era) will determine if it can find new growth in t=
he years to come. For now, Apple=E2=80=99s Q1 results affirm the company=E2=
=80=99s incredible strengths, but also illuminate the areas it must strateg=
ically address. And if there=E2=80=99s one thing Apple=E2=80=99s history sh=
ows, it=E2=80=99s that the company is adept at playing the long game =E2=80=
=93 exactly what will be needed for Services to keep flourishing, for China=
 to be navigated, and for AI to become a true differentiator rather than a =
footnote in the quarterly earnings script.

